    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            From the learner experience, we observe that depreciation reduces the value of an asset by a fixed percentage each year.
        </p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> A = \amp \; P - I </mrow>
                <mrow> I = \amp \; \frac{R}{100} \times P </mrow>
                <mrow> A = \amp \; P - \frac{R}{100} \times P </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp \; P \left(1 - \frac{R}{100}\right) </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>
            Since the value decreases every year, each new value becomes the starting value for the next year.
        </p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{After Year 1: } A = \amp \; P \left(1 - \frac{R}{100}\right) </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{After Year 2: } A = \amp \; P \left(1 - \frac{R}{100}\right)^2 </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{After Year 3: } A = \amp \; P \left(1 - \frac{R}{100}\right)^3 </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>
            In general, after <m>T</m> years, the value of the asset is given by:
            <m> A = P \left(1 - \frac{R}{100}\right)^T </m>.
        </p>

        <p>
            This shows that depreciation is not a constant decrease but a repeated percentage reduction, where the value reduces on a decreasing base over time.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                An Iron box costs sh. <m>500</m>. Every year it depreciates by <m>10\%</m> of its value at the beginning of that year. What will its value be after <m>4</m> years?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Value after the first year}\; = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; (500 - \frac{10}{100}\times 500) </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; 450 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Value after the second year}\; = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; (450 - \frac{10}{100}\times 450) </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; 405 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Value after the third year}\; = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; (405 - \frac{10}{100}\times 405) </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; 364.50 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Value after the fourth year}\; = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; (364.50 - \frac{10}{100}\times 364.50) </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; 328.05 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                This shows that the value of the iron box after four years is <m>500(1-\frac{10}{100})^4 </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                In general, if P is the initial value of an asset, A the value after depreciation for n periods and r the rate of depreciation per period;
            </p>
            <p>
                <m> \text{A}\; = \;\text{P}( 1- \frac{\text{r}}{100})^n </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A minibus costs sh. <m>400,000</m>. Due to wear and tear, it depreciates in value by <m>2\%</m> every month. Find the value after one year.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <m> \text{A}\; = \;\text{P}( 1- \frac{\text{r}}{100})^n </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Substituting P <m> = 400,000</m>, r <m> = 2</m>, and n <m> = 12</m> in the formula;
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{A}\; = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; 400,000(1-0.02)^{12} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; 400,000(0.98)^{12} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; \text{sh.}\; 313,700 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>

